# View Conventions

## Views Are HTML with Sprinkles

Views render the model for the browser. They are HTML documents with the minimum Ruby necessary to display data. If a view has conditionals that compute derived state or branch on business rules — that logic belongs elsewhere. Simple formatting methods (`truncate`, `humanize`, `titleize`, `time_ago_in_words`) are fine inline.

```erb
<%# Good — view reads like annotated HTML %>
<article>
  <h1><%= @article.title %></h1>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500"><%= @article.byline %></p>
  <p class="text-xs text-gray-400"><%= time_ago_in_words(@article.created_at) %> ago</p>
  <%= render @article.comments %>
</article>

<%# Bad — computation and business logic in the template %>
<article>
  <h1><%= @article.title %></h1>
  <p>
    By <%= @article.creator.first_name %> <%= @article.creator.last_name %>
    <% if @article.updated_at > @article.created_at + 1.hour %>
      (edited)
    <% end %>
    <% if @article.comments.where(flagged: true).any? %>
      <span class="text-red-600">Has flagged comments</span>
    <% end %>
  </p>
</article>
```

Push domain predicates to models (`article.edited?`, `article.byline`), reusable formatting to helpers, and reusable markup to partials.

**User-facing static copy** — use **`t()`** / **`I18n.t`** and keys under **`config/locales`**, not raw strings scattered through ERB. Lazy lookup, interpolation, and key structure: **`rules/i18n.mdc`**, **`skills/writing-i18n/references/patterns.md`**.

## Partials with Strict Locals

Every partial declares its interface with `locals:` magic comments. No instance variables in partials — they receive everything through locals.

```erb
<%# app/views/articles/_article.html.erb %>
<%# locals: (article:) %>
<article id="<%= dom_id(article) %>" class="border-b border-gray-200 py-4">
  <h2><%= link_to article.title, article, class: "text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 hover:text-blue-600" %></h2>
  <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-600"><%= article.summary %></p>
</article>
```

Render with explicit locals:

```erb
<%= render "articles/article", article: @article %>
<%= render partial: "articles/article", collection: @articles %>
<%= render @articles %>
```

The short form `render @articles` works when the partial matches the model name.

## Collection Rendering

Render collections with `render @collection` — Rails resolves the partial automatically and handles empty states:

```erb
<%= render @articles %>
<%= render(@articles) || tag.p("No articles yet.", class: "text-gray-500 italic py-8") %>
```

## Styling with Tailwind

Utility classes go directly in the ERB markup. The HTML *is* the component in Rails — partials provide reuse, not CSS abstractions. Use **`class_names`** for conditional utilities; helpers may return class strings when the same pattern repeats across templates.

```erb
<div class="flex items-center gap-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900"><%= article.title %></h3>
  <span class="rounded-full bg-green-100 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-green-700">
    Published
  </span>
</div>
```

**Pipeline and global CSS** — `tailwindcss-rails`, Tailwind **v3 vs v4** config shape, `@apply` policy, extending the theme, dark/responsive conventions: **`rules/css-tailwind.mdc`**, **`skills/writing-css-tailwind/references/patterns.md`**. Template-level patterns (partials, `class_names`, forms): this rule and **`skills/writing-views/references/patterns.md`** § Tailwind.

## Helpers for Presentation Logic

Helpers format data for display. They return strings and take values as arguments — no side effects, no state.

```ruby
module ArticlesHelper
  def reading_time(article)
    minutes = (article.body.split.size / 200.0).ceil
    pluralize(minutes, "min read")
  end

  def status_badge(article)
    classes = class_names(
      "rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium",
      "bg-green-100 text-green-700": article.published?,
      "bg-gray-100 text-gray-600": !article.published?
    )
    tag.span(article.published? ? "Published" : "Draft", class: classes)
  end
end
```

Use helpers for:
- Formatting (dates, numbers, currency, text)
- Conditional CSS class composition with `class_names`
- Small composed elements (badge with icon, link with label)
- Wrapping Rails helpers with domain defaults

## Stimulus and Turbo (Hotwire)

Stimulus controllers live in **`app/javascript/controllers/`** — `data-controller`, `data-action`, targets — not inline `<script>` tags. Importmap vs bundling, entrypoints, and not fighting the pipeline: **`rules/javascript.mdc`**, **`skills/writing-javascript/references/patterns.md`**. Turbo Frames wrap regions that update in isolation; stream templates use **`action.turbo_stream.erb`**. Full patterns, morphing, broadcasts, and accidental-SPA anti-patterns: **`skills/writing-hotwire/references/patterns.md`**. Rule: **`rules/hotwire.mdc`**.

## Links and Buttons

`link_to` for navigation (GET). `button_to` for mutations (POST/PATCH/DELETE).

```erb
<%# Navigation — link %>
<%= link_to "View article", article_path(@article), class: "text-blue-600 hover:underline" %>

<%# Mutation — button %>
<%= button_to "Delete", article_path(@article), method: :delete,
      class: "text-red-600 hover:text-red-800 text-sm font-medium",
      data: { turbo_confirm: "Delete this article?" } %>
```

## Layouts and Content Blocks

Use `content_for` / `yield` to inject page-specific content into layouts. Use `provide` when setting a single value, `content_for` when building up content with blocks.

```erb
<%# app/views/articles/show.html.erb %>
<% provide(:title, @article.title) %>
```

## Form Conventions

Use `form_with` bound to a model. It infers the URL, method, and Turbo behaviour automatically:

```erb
<%= form_with model: @article, class: "space-y-4" do |f| %>
  <div>
    <%= f.label :title, class: "block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700" %>
    <%= f.text_field :title, class: "mt-1 block w-full rounded-md border-gray-300 shadow-sm focus:border-blue-500 focus:ring-blue-500" %>
  </div>

  <%= f.submit class: "rounded-md bg-blue-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-blue-700" %>
<% end %>
```

Show validation errors inline, close to the field — not as a detached error summary.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Instance variables in partials | Strict locals (`locals:` magic comment) |
| Business logic / queries in views | Controller sets instance variables, model owns predicates |
| `if/else` trees for rendering variants | Separate partials or polymorphic rendering |
| Inline `<script>` or `<style>` in templates | Stimulus controllers, Tailwind utilities |
| `link_to` for mutations (DELETE, POST) | `button_to` with `method:` |
| `@apply` for every styled block | Extract a partial — partials are your components |
| Arbitrary Tailwind values everywhere (`bg-[#1a2b3c]`) | Extend the Tailwind config with project tokens |
| Hardcoded CSS class strings repeated across templates | Helper returning class string, or extract partial |
| Rendering partials without locals declaration | Add `<%# locals: (...) %>` magic comment |
| HTML string concatenation in helpers | `tag` builder or partials |
| `Current.user` checks inside partials | Pass permission as boolean local, or use model predicate at the template level |
